pythonfor it in out["intents"]:
    candidates = it.get("final_candidates") or []
    if include_retrieval_signals:
        # Candidates first — the intent's temporal is derived from theirs.
        for fc in candidates:
            fc["retrieval_signals"] = result._structured_signals(
                fc.get("retrieval_signals") or {}
            )
        it["retrieval_signals"] = result._structured_signals(
            it.get("retrieval_signals") or {}
        )
        # Intent temporal = deduped union (by cui) of its candidates' already
        # resolved temporal.
        if candidates:
            merged: List[Dict[str, Any]] = []
            seen: set = set()
            for fc in candidates:
                for t in fc["retrieval_signals"].get("temporal") or []:
                    key = t.get("codes")
                    if key not in seen:
                        seen.add(key)
                        merged.append(t)
            it["retrieval_signals"]["temporal"] = merged
Two things changed: (1) candidates are resolved before the intent, since the intent derives from them; (2) the intent's temporal is overwritten with the deduped union of its candidates' temporal.
The bug it fixes: the intent used to resolve its own raw temporal phrases against the vocabulary file, independently of its candidates. Any phrase with no matching concept was dropped — and if some other phrase did resolve, the fallback never fired, so it disappeared silently. The intent ended up listing fewer temporals than its own candidates. record_types never had this because plain strings need no resolution. Now temporal unions across candidates the same way record_types does.
